charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us. To
donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk
charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Toolstation are proud to be partnering with Macmillan Cancer Support for the next two years.

There are currently 3 million people living with cancer in the UK, with someone receiving a cancer diagnosis every two minutes. We know that one in two people in the UK will experience a cancer diagnosis in their lifetime.

For more than 100 years Macmillan has been there for people with cancer when they needed them most.  Today is no exception!

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing physical, financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Our mum, Ann Ashmore, developed breast cancer in 2003 and also in 2012. On both occasions, she successfully beat the disease with radiotherapy and a mastectomy. In November 2020, we sadly discovered that her cancer had returned for the third time but had spread to other parts of her body which saw Mum’s health decline rapidly. On Monday 8th February, Mum lost her life to this awful disease after months of pain and discomfort. 

MacMillan supported the family during Mum’s last few months at home and in hospital, and for this, we are very grateful.

We are kindly asking for donations to be sent to Macmillan to continue to help and support the wonderful work they do.

Love the Ashmore family ❤️

story:
I blame this entirely on my lovely friend Kate Burningham in Devon, she is doing the same fundraiser and requested people join her for a jog.  Kate and her family were helped by Macmillan nurses when her husband developed cancer.  Due to living in different county's I am unable to run and support her....to be fair I'm unable to run anywhere! 

I have also lost my Uncle Ray to cancer this year and have other friends that have had cancer touch their lives.  Therefore I thought if I can't run with Kate, I'll run the same distance and hopefully raise a bit of cash.

I'm 4 stone overweight, lazy as hell and would rather eat cake and watch television than run but I will achieve this if you bung us a couple of quid.  Feel free to join on me on my many slow jogs over the next month....don't expect conversation as I will barely be able to breath let alone speak....

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

In Memory of Malc (9th August 1936-10th Feb 2021) 

For those who knew Malcolm  it’s an opportunity to share your memories with family members. I know my dad touched so many lives during his lifetime and he would often recall good times he had with family and friends.

A great sportsman, loving the game of football- his memories at Blackpool FC, Manchester United (reserves as part of the Busby Babes),Ashton United and Mossley often filled the house as he reminisced about his time with top players. After retirement from football he continued in sport, moving to coaching javelin at the local athletic clubs East Cheshire and Trafford A.C.

Please share your memories if Malcolm- the family would love to read them!

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. 

St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.  

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." 
Tom Willis, volunteer 

Will you support me and help make a difference?

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Kier Group has selected the British Heart Foundation, the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK, as its new corporate charity partner. The two-year partnership will help in the charitys aim of increasing awareness of cardiovascular disease, raise £250,000 for vital research in to heart and circulatory conditions as well as train 1,500 Kier colleagues in the lifesaving first aid, CPR.

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
In June 2012 I was diagnosed with a heart condition called Long QT Syndrome (LQTS). At the time I was experiencing intense palpitations and feeling like I was going to pass out. An ECG suggested I had LQTS, and I was referred to see a cardiologist. This appointment was pretty life changing as I was told this condition could cause sudden death. It was 2 days before my 30th birthday, and I was sent home with a 24hour monitor, beta blockers and strict instructions not to do anything that would cause an increase in heart rate...not easy in every day life! Being told particular triggers were cold water, swimming and intense exercise, my birthday plans for an inflatable assault course on Loch Lomond followed by a week in a fitness resort in Lanzarote were swiftly cancelled! 🤣

Following my diagnosis I experienced severe anxiety and panic attacks - I was terrified I was going to just drop one day! It made me scared to go out myself, in case there was no one with me to tell paramedics etc about my condition and the fact I would probably need a defibrillator. This was really debilitating, but with the love and support of my amazing family and friends, I gradually started to adjust. 

About 6 months later, genetic testing confirmed this was genetic, as we suspected, as my dear granny had been diagnosed in later life. She was a legend and a trouper, so a great inspiration, which gave me confidence that it could all be ok ☺️

Since then I have learned to live with my condition, I take beta blockers every day, and live a fairly normal and active life, which I am very grateful for! 

When my darling Son was born, we knew there was a 50% chance he would inherit this condition, but despite this I still felt floored when they told me he had it 😔 He was so tiny and vulnerable, and I felt terrified at the prospect of anything happening to him. Like a right little trouper, he had ECGs and tests, and at 5 days old we were readmitted to hospital to start him on propranolol 3 x daily, as his QT was particularly prolonged. We were told he had an increased risk of cot death, which again devastated me, as I just wanted to protect my little bundle with every ounce of my being! He was such a brave boy, and still is, and continues to take his meds like such a superstar. 

Due to my condition, I also had some complications post partum, which led to 3 hospital stays, tests, medication changes, the fitting of a monitoring device, and a lot of worry, but thankfully, I am doing much better now, and am so grateful for all the care and treatment I received ☺️

Right now, I am doing fine, and thankfully so is my darling little boy! I have always planned to fundraise in order to support further research, and Zachary’s diagnosis has spurred me on to stop procrastinating and do what we can to help!

With this is mind, I plan to run/walk 100k in March to raise money for the British Heart Foundation ❤️ The runs will be my challenge, and the walks will be Zachary’s contribution as he supports this cause too 💙

Thank you for reading our story, to find out more about LQTS follow this link - 

https://www.bhf.org.uk/informationsupport/conditions/long-qt-syndrome

and to all who are able to donate, thank you from the bottom of our hearts 🥰

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
On the 3rd of December 2016 My dad passed away unexpectedly from heart disease. He was always the life and soul of any get together, from setting himself on fire with petrol(accidently) to just have great banter and having a laugh. 

He was the reason I enjoyed gaming so much, we used to play games online every evening together. So I will be attempting to do a 24 hour live stream in honor of him for his upcoming birthday. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK, however. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. 

£25 could pay for an hour of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I’m Alexis and I am 8 years old, I am going to give up chocolate for March to raise money for the British heart foundation. Right now the British heart foundation really needs our help, because of Covid they aren’t getting enough money for research  

Their research is very important and has to carry on because they are finding ways to help people with heart illnesses like my mum  

I love chocolate so this is going to be hard to do, but I know I can do it because helping is more important to me than eating chocolate  

Please sponsor me and my parents to give up chocolate  

your sponsorship will go straight to the British heart foundation  

Thank you

From Alexis

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
So, I’ve decided to do the Dechox for another year to help raise funds for British Heart Foundation and for vital life changing research. Quitting chocolate for a whole month to raise money and help save lives. Unfortunately due to the pandemic BHF has had to cut their research by half due to lack of funds, that’s why we need people like you more than ever to help raise money for this amazing cause.

Let’s come together to make a difference. I am doing this in loving memory of those we’ve lost with heart disease or heart failure.

On this Dechox, I am cutting out all chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks. I’m doing it because I want to help and make a difference, also a good health kick always does you good. I mean what’s one month without chocolate compared to saving lives from raising money for this worthy cause? It’s a no brainer! Please help me on this. Every single penny helps however big or small. I will post updates on my progress and hope you can join me on this journey! Thank you for all your support. Wish me luck! ❤️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: February happens to be Marfan Syndrome Awareness Month, and it was also my 18th birthday this month. I and many others have cardiac issues, and research is vital for supporting people such as myself to improve quality of life and even sometimes cure their illnesses. I know many people (including family members) who have experienced major cardiac events, or have heart conditions they couldn't cope with without medications, surgery, or other things that require extensive research and funding. So, if you can spare a little money or even just share this page, I'll be extremely grateful! I won't be eating sweets, chocolate, or having ANY fizzy drinks this month to help fundraise, so wish me luck!!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation as many of you may know we lost my Mam very suddenly in 2019 due to a massive heart block following valve surgery and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

Also as many of you may also know I am a CHOCOHOLIC!!! So this is going to be a challenge for me!!! But I know my heart will thank me for it in the long run, So dig deep people!! 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I did this a few years back in honour of a really good friend and neighbour, Steve Boshell. And I’m doing it again! 

I know if I do this in his memory, I won’t touch chocolate, sweets or fizzy drinks because he will be shouting at me from wherever he is with his booming voice saying, “oi you fat fecker, step away from the chocolate!”

This is the least I can do in his memory as pay back for all of the hours he mended my bikes, mopeds and cars! 

Always in my heart and thoughts Steve 💕

Sue - you’re alright too xxx

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Myself and Tiernan will not touch a drop of chocolate in March, so we can raise money for the British Heart foundation. This is very important to us. Tiernan has a heart condition (Pulmanory Stenosis) which he has had since birth, he had a balloon dilatation in 2017 and it went really well 😊💙 this is a condition he will have for life so will forever need monitoring, and thankfully all is still good. But if it wasn't for the research and hard work of these doctor's and nurse's thing's could be very different.

story: Well I'm giving up Chocolate for a month,anyone who knows me will know how hard this is going to be for me. I lost my dad in 2001 to a massive heart attack without warning he was gone at the age of 55. Recently another relative had the same heart attack luckily they survived it. Everyone's mind is on covid at the moment but, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends please donate what you can afford. All donations will be truly grateful accepted. 🙏❤️

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
It was Dot's wish that we raise a little something for the British Heart Foundation. Because of the research that they do, a lot of our family have benefited. Having lost her husband at an early age to heart disease, and Nan taking part in the research trials for statins, she considered this a very worthy cause. Rather than floral tributes, she asked that anyone who can to make a small donation in her memory.

Thank you.




Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation because it’s time that we raise awareness about heart disease. 

But I also want to remember two very special people.

Both my dear mummy, Elizabeth Wells-Sheppard, and brother, Alexander Sheppard, have passed away in recent years due to arterial blockage, a genetic heart condition. Both deaths were sudden, completely unexpected and showed no signs or symptoms of onset.

This month, my mummy would have been 70 and just over a month ago, Alex would have been 49; both taken long before they should have been. 

I would really appreciate you donating to my fundraiser! Heart disease is something that does not receive near enough exposure as it should. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. 

Thank you for reading my story!

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
My names Leah. I’m a student Radiographer in the north of England and I’m guilty for being a choco-aholic with a huge sweet tooth! I’m doing this March dechox not only to challenge myself to stop my bad habits, but also to raise an awareness for The BHF along with a bit of fundraising! 

This is going to be a HUGE challenge for me as chocolate, sweets & frizzy drinks are a massive comfort to me! So by signing up to this challenge I am hoping to smash my personal goals!

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
To anybody that knows me well, they will know that I love my chocolate and probably eat too much of it on a daily basis. As a cardiac nurse I have decided to give the money for my chocolate fund to a cause close to my heart. There is still a lot of research needed to keep improving treatment and care for heart patients to give them a better quality of life. Thank you to each and every one of you who reads/shares or donates to help our ❤️ patients.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. On the 1st July 2005, my beautiful granddaughter was born, Ruby Rose Tranter. 

None of us realised that she was born with a heart defect called tetralogy of fallot. This was discovered at nearly 10 months old. At 10 months old, she had emergency open heart surgery. 

She is now nearly 16, a pair of eyebrows and a phone! But she is my world. We talk, we giggle, we laugh, we love. 

I tell her i love her more than chocolate! So I'm going to prove that this month by giving it up! 

Thankyou for reading my story xxx

story: Hi my name is Henry and I am not eating chocolate for the whole of March to raise money for a charity close to my heart. This charity has looked after me since I was a baby. Many of you reading this have been on the journey with me and know how poorly I was when I was born. I feel really sad that Covid has meant charities like the BHF have lost lots of fund raising, so I’m trying to help. If you would like to sponsor me and donate even just £1 I would be so happy!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Anyone who knows me well knows I cannot go a day without eating something sweet or chocolatey. However I have decided to take on the British Heart Foundation challenge of giving up all things sweet/chocolatey for the month of March to raise some money for their much needed research. Heart and circulatory diseases cause more than 1/4 of all deaths in the UK and unfortunately the pandemic has had a substantial impact on the research and researchers the British Heart Foundation are funding! Therefore, I believe me giving up some treats is a very small sacrifice to try and help their cause. Any contribution you can make is greatly appreciated!

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Following my Aunt's death in 2015, members of my family including myself discovered that we are at high risk of Cardiovascular Disease (CVD). Since then, I've continued to support the British Heart Foundation as much as possible as well as be in the fortunate position to call the charity my workplace too! Since then, I've ran the Great North Run, walked 100km in a day, taken on the famous London to Brighton Bike Ride and trekked in Peru to Machu Picchu...but this March will be my biggest challenge yet, giving up something I love more than anything in the world! No, not Greggs, but bread! Bread is my life...but in March I'm giving it up, with sweets, chocolate and fizzy drinks for 2 reasons...to raise money for a charity I love, but to also try and get back to fitness! 

Thanks for checking out my page and helping me fundraise...hugely appreciate it and anything you can do to help me through this bread-less month will really help me!

story:
I am doing Dechox for the month of March to raise money for British Heart Foundation❤️ This may not seem like a huge challenge for people but for those who know me, they know how much of a challenge this will be for me! No chocolate for 31 days 😱

Any money I raise will help with life saving research and be part of a movement to beat heartbreak forever. Every pound I help to raise will go towards funding vital research into heart and circulatory diseases. 


If anyone would like to donate, any donations no matter the amount would be hugely appreciated ✨

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: June 22nd 2007 at the age of 17 I lost my wonderful Mum to a rare and incurable heart disease 😭💔 which is called Arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy or ARVC. Unfortunately no one was aware she had this until the day she had multiple cardiac arrests and died shortly after arriving at hospital. So after this happened me and my sisters had regular tests as I’m the disease is hereditary. Not long after having my second child I found I that I have this disease and have had a icd fitted  2 years ago which will not cure anything but should save my life should my heart goes into an arrhythmia or cardiac arrest. Like I said this disease is incurable but the British heart foundation and cardiologist are learning more each day about this disease and hopefully in the future there could be a cure or something that could help. So in memory of my mum and for myself I am going to give up all chocolate, sweets and all fizzy drinks for the whole of March. And as some of you know me giving up a certain fizzy drink will be so hard for me. So please support me. How ever little or large the donation. It will help. Thank you for reading and supporting me xxx

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Heart desease has been a part of our family history.   On the 20th Dec 2020 I woke up with a tight chest and a achy arm. After speaking to someone at 111 they noticed the signs and sent an ambulance. I was taken to my local hospital where I suffered another episode. I was told by the cardiac doctor I had suffered a heart attack and was being taken to a London hospital where I could be treated. Transfered via ambulance complete with lights and sirens. I arrived to be met by a team of doctors and nurses who rushed me in to be fitted with a stent.  So going from someone who was always rushing around, never needing to go to the doctors  to being laid up and on 6 different tablets a day for life. The British heart foundation has been a great help for info and care to me.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
We will be covering a marathon distance over 24 hours. Three miles in the first hour and then one mile every hour thereafter. Gordon hall is our current uni accommodation and we will be operating within covid guidelines. Along the way we will be picking up litter, singing, wearing costumes and probably some other nonsense too (The last mile is also a beer mile). If you have any suggestions to add to this then add a message to your donation. We are happy to send proof. Everybody in the photos will be taking part plus a few others.



British heart foundation is a charity close to many of our hearts and we have seen the incredible work they do. Many, if not all of us, know someone who has had or has been affected by a heart-related condition and hope that with our donation we can be a part of the research that will eventually put an end to many people's suffering.

story: In memory of my late father Frank Stuart I am raising funds by selling items of antiques, collectors and ornamental items over the sale sites of Swindon and market place towards Guide Dogs for the Blind. My father donated money to the charity a few months before he passed away, now I want to help to raise more funds in his memory. My dad wasn't blind he died of lung cancer but it was his dying wish to meet a guide dog before he passed. Alan Fletcher gave us that wish and we want to support Alan and Guide dogs for the blind. It costs approx £63,000 from pup to retirement for each guide dog. By selling charitable items I hope we can as a community raise money together for such a worth while cause. Thanks Wendy

story:
Gary Hindle lost his battle with a long illness on 20th January 2021. 

He was a 'larger than life' character, a man that filled every room that he entered and who will be sadly missed by David, Marcia & Michael and his many friends, colleagues, and family.

Gary loved dogs, and it was his wish that we raise money for a canine charity, so we are collecting donations in his memory for the Guide dogs for the Blind.

While you reflect upon how much to donate; below are just some of the great things that people said about our friend Gary. Please give generously.

"I really feel honoured and privileged to have had such a loyal, funny, loveable big softy as my best friend and I will miss him".

"You had a profound impact on all our lives, and we were all better for having known you".

"He was a great professional and hard worker and gave a lot of  employers a lot more hard work than they paid for".

"He was a superb guy. A really decent chap"  

This page has been set up on behalf of David and Marcia Hindle.

regards 

Graham Perry

story:
Evie is going to be walking 2 miles a day in March to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital and Children's Charity. 

Would anyone like to sponsor her? Even a small amount would be fabulous 💜

Want to join Evie in supporting a good cause? I'm raising money for Great Ormond Street Hospital and Children's Charity and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate £5 or £500. Every little bit helps. Thank you for your support. I've included information about Great Ormond Street Hospital and Children's Charity below.

Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. Together with our research partner, the UCL Institute of Child Health (ICH), we form the UK’s only academic biomedical research centre specialising in paediatrics.

Since its formation in 1852, the hospital has been dedicated to children’s healthcare and to finding new and better ways to treat childhood illnesses.

Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity raises money to enable the hospital to provide world class care and to pioneer new treatments and cures for childhood illnesses.

With over 220,000 patient visits every year, we need your support to help us give hope to our young patients and their families.

story:
I’m raising money for GOSH as 5 years ago I had scoliosis surgery at Great Ormond St and this changed my everyday life for the better and I would love to do something to give back and as a thank you for the amazing work they do.

I decided to do 5k a day for the 5 years since my op, and I picked to do it during April as my operation was 28th April 2016. 

The daily 5k’s will be a mix of running and walking as I will be completely them around college, work and playing tennis ( which has become a huge part of my life since my operation as it is one of the only sport I can do and has also had a huge impact on my long term recovery )

I am appreciative of any donations and thank you for your support xxx

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

eventName: TeamSport South GM'S Run The Region
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Great Ormond Street Hospital is the UK's largest paediatric centre for many services including heart problems, brain surgery and gene therapy. They are an international centre of excellence in child healthcare and the UK's only paediatric National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Biomedical Research Centre (BRC).

It's also close the heart of one of our team who have depended on their services since the birth of their Daughter.

What are we doing and why?

Trying to keep healthy, motivated and active during what has been by far a tough winter, has not been easy!

Our mental health aswell as physical health is so important and to help, Lolly King (TeamSport Crawley GM) has thrown out a welcomed challenge!

The South region management team will run the distance it takes to travel between our tracks!.... Only 206 miles! :-O

A virtual baton will be passed between 13 of us who can walk, hop, skip or run any length of the target!

A TOTAL OF 206 MILES BY SUNDAY 11TH APRIL

Eastleigh to Gosport 18 miles

Gosport to Brighton 47 miles

Brighton to Crawley 25 miles

Crawley to Mitcham 23 miles

Mitcham to Acton 10 miles

Acton to Docklands 17 miles

Docklands to Edmonton 17 miles

Edmonton to Harlow 21 miles

Harlow to Basildon 28 miles


We'll be posting updates and proof of the miles we put on the clock and in return would love your moral (and financial) support for this great cause!


Thank you!


The TeamSport South Region Management Team

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
I will be running the Virtual London Marathon in October of this year in support of Great Ormond Street Hospital. A virtual marathon involves running the distance of a marathon along a route of your choice on the date in question, any time between 00:01am and midnight. I will probably need all 24 of those hours to get round, but will provisionally be aiming to finish in around 4 hours. 

My running partner is my extraordinary mate and ex-work wife Katie (the split was amicable - we both got new jobs). Katie spent a year working as an English teacher on the wards of Great Ormond Street, teaching poetry and creative writing to many quite wonderful and brave young people. Her accounts of working at GOSH confirmed what I think we all already know: it is an extraordinary place full of brave, resilient healthcare professionals and even braver young people. 

So give what you can, if you can! All in aid of an excellent cause.

So last year I done a bike ride to Brighton, for a charity close to home. This year I wanna go a bit further and walk to Brighton. I will be donating money to Great Ormand Street children’s hospital. 


I’ll be starting my walk on Friday the 11th of June and hopefully getting to Brighton on the 12th at some time , so around 24hours😂 going by how long it took my to cycle there, Probally be even longer 😂


I’ve chosen Great Ormand Street as I think it’s a good charity, and no child deserves to be in there.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I lost my Nan, Kathleen Wright, to breast cancer June 14th 2000. I was 10 years old and my Nan was only 59! When diagnosed she was told the cancer would be cleared in 5 years but sadly it spread into her lymph glands and took her earlier. 

I have so many fond memories of my Nan and the lovely things she would do. She was such a strong, kind, and unconditionally loving lady. One memory that always comes to mind was her stash of fresh soft blueberry bonbons in the old school sweet tubs that she used to keep in the pub kitchen. Whenever me and my family visited she would get the tub out and share them with the children. Another was her fantastic Sunday roasts, nothing beats them to this day, apart from my wife’s and maybe my mums ;) 

When I told my family I wanted to raise money for a charity in memory of my Nan my grandad Peter Wright along with my uncle Jeffrey Wright suggested i raised money for the Marie Curie trust as my Nan would often refer to this trust during her cancer treatment.

I will be challenging myself to run a minimum of 1 mile a day for 365 days. This will most definitely be a challenge as i have a reasonably physically demanding job, working long days for mostly 6-7 days a week. I also have a large family of 6 including myself so finding the time to run will be difficult. Most of my runs will be commuting to or from work, very early mornings or late evenings. 

Thank you for taking the time to read my ‘short’ story, wish me luck!

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This page is to honour a life-long faithful friend, colleague and mentor - Frances Heggie who sadly passed away last weekend – much too early.

Frances was a humble and generous lady who left a lasting impression on a huge amount of people and she will be sadly missed by her many friends and colleagues not only at Scottish Widows but across the Protection industry.

To honour Frances, this page is to commemorate the friendship she brought to many throughout her career. The contribution she made to our industry and in particular her contribution to underwriting, brought innovation, enthusiasm but mostly compassion and her legacy will remain with many who have leading roles across our industry today.

Our thoughts and condolences are with her husband David and family.  If you’d like to join in commemorating the great memories we all have of Frances, her husband David has suggested making a donation to Marie Curie. The  Edinburgh branch chosen is an  excellent local charity we often support.  All money raised will ensure more people living with a terminal illness can access free care from Marie Curie Nurses when they need it most.

For further information on Marie Curie Edinburgh visit 
https://www.mariecurie.org.uk/help/hospice-care/edinburgh

 Thank You

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Our nurses, doctors, therapists and social workers provide expert care and support both to the people staying with us at the hospice, and in the local community. 

Each day at the hospice is special. By getting to know people as individuals, we help them do what is important to them  whether thats getting out into the hospice garden to enjoy the views across the sea, having a beloved pet visit come to visit or sharing precious moments with their loved ones.

We need to raise £8,311 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Cardiff and the Vale get the care and support they need.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story: I recently decided I wanted to make a conscious effort to walk or run more steps in March so what better way to do it than by raising some money for an amazing cause in the process. I honestly believe the people that work for Marie Curie are real life hero’s, I like to think of myself as a very strong person but even I don’t think I could do the job they do every single day. It must be the most heartbreaking but also rewarding job, to know how comfortable you’ve made someone and their families in those final moments of life. So everyday in March I will be walking or running 10,000 steps to a grand total of 310’000 by the 31st! Any donation you can make however big or small would be incredible 🖤

Any donations would be great even a £5 is fab x

story: We are each going to be running, cycling or walking a minimum of 100 miles in March in support of WWF UK. We are all passionate about the planet and want to help in any way we can. It’s also an excuse to get fit during lockdown! WWF UK‘s mission is to stop the degredation of the planet’s natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature. To do this, WWF works with a broad spectrum of partners including governments, industry, and local communities to find solutions to the challenges that face our natural world.

story:
I am walking the 33km section of the Jurassic Challenge from Corfe Castle to Weymouth in May. It is the hardest section of a longer walk because it has the steepest climbs including Lulworth and Durdle Door. It is going to be a challenge for me as it is the longest walk I have done, but I am going to train hard and eat my veg! 

I am raising money for the WWF because they are a charity I hold close to my heart. I hope one day to work for them as a conservationist. If you feel you can support me I would be grateful for any amount you can give. 

 WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: Oxfam
eventName: World Water Day UEA Oxfam Walk
story:
Members of UEA Oxfam Society are walking 10km on World Water Day to raise money for Oxfam. Some members will also be carrying weights to symbolise the weight carried by people who have to walk to collect water.

785 million people worldwide don't have clean water close to home, and have to walk long distances to collect water. Please donate to our page to help Oxfam supply people globally with safe, clean water and hygiene facilities. 

Check out updates on the event on our Instagram @ueaoxfamsoc

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. charity.name: Unicef UK
eventName: 2 Miles on the Hour for Unicef
story:
Remember when Bob Geldof did Live Aid and raised loadsa f'in muney for those suffering from famine in Ethiopia? Well, this is a little less glitzy than Live Aid as I haven't really got the contacts to pull that off... 

But I would like to raise money for UNICEF who provide life saving nutrition, clean water, education, vaccines etc, etc to children and families in 190 counties worldwide. Seeing babies, children suffering, starving to death in 2021 breaks my heart in to tiny pieces and I have to do what I can to try raise money to help.

And I can run. So I've decided to challenge myself to run 2 miles, every hour, on the hour, within 12hrs on Sunday 28th March 2021. (Daylight savings for that extra light!) 

So, that is 24 miles in 12hrs, with around 40mins in between to rest, eat, toilet and cuddle our toddler. Sounds easy but I don't think it will be...

I'd love you to sponsor me and therefore donate to UNICEF. Please give what you can. I'd be so happy to know that someone supports my challenge and this cause.

Thank you for reading.

Much love.

Debs xxx

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
I will try to go 4km per €1 raised, and I hope to get a lot of support. Hopefully, I'll be able to keep up with the contributions - but I'm always up for a challenge ;-)



I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. story:

Building the infrastructure, including safe and drinkable water, is often depending on us and on our donors, and we are grateful for any support."

CMS CEE Quiz Night is taking place on 22 March 2021. 

We are asking for a minimum donation of EUR 5 to support our charity partner Médecins Sans Frontières and the superb work they do around the world ensuring that people in refugee camps have access to fresh, clean, drinkable water.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
An expedition to Mars to look for water, or provide clean water for the 1 in 10 people on this planet who don’t have access to this basic necessity - Something I just can’t get my head around!

The head shaving will begin when £240 has been raised (enough to put a well in two villages) ... When I get to £360, you get to see the ‘Full Monty’ photo!

Thank you for supporting me in this xx

Clean  water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives.

story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
title: Carla
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: Carla

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
